
Accessible; A wine that is easy to drink without an overwhelming sense of tannin, acidity or extract.
Acidic; A wine with a noticeable sense of acidity. Acid gives the wine a lively, crisp quality.
Aerate; To allow a wine to “breathe” by exposing it to oxygen to help it to mellow and develop its full flavors, i.e. thru decanting. 
Aftertaste; A term for the taste left on the palate after wine has been swallowed. "Finish" is a synonym.
Aggressive; A wine with harsh and pronounced flavors due to too much tannin. The opposite of a wine described as "smooth" or "soft"
Alcoholic; A wine that has an out of balanced presence of too much alcohol.
Astringent; A mouth puckering sensation caused by the acid and tannin in a wine. 
Appellation; One specific geographic area from which a wine is produced. Most European wines are named by appellation rather than grape varietal.
Aroma; The smell of the young wine. The direct aromas of the grape varietal.
Aromatic; When the smell of the grape is apparent as in Muscat and Gewürztraminer wines 
Baked; A wine with a high alcohol content that gives the perception of stewed or baked fruit flavors. May indicate a wine from grapes that were exposed to the heat of the sun after harvesting.
Balanced; A wine that incorporates all its main components—tannins, acid, sweetness, and alcohol—in a harmonic manner where no one single component stands out.
Big; A wine with intense flavor, or high in alcohol. Often used to describe a “full-bodied” wine.
Biscuity; A wine with a sense of yeasty or bread dough aroma and flavors. Applicable for Champagne.
Bite; A firm and distinctive perception of tannins or acidity. This can be a positive or negative attribute depending on whether the overall perception of the wine is balanced.
Bitter; An unpleasant perception of tannins.
Blowzy; An exaggerated fruity aroma. Commonly associated with lower quality fruity wines.
Body; The sense of alcohol in the wine and the sense of feeling in the mouth.
Botrytis; Or Nobel rot, a fungus that removes water from the grapes, leaving behind a higher percent of solids, such as sugars, fruit acids and minerals, which results in a more intense, concentrated final product. 
Bouquet; Name for the smell of the mature wine. The bouquet is made up of all the layers of smells and aromas perceived in a wine.
Buttery; A wine that has a rich, creamy mouthfeel with flavors reminiscent of butter.
Cassis; The French term for the flavors associated with black currant. 
Cedarwood; A collective term used to describe the woodsy aroma of a wine that has been treated with oak.
Character; The features of a wine that distinguish it from any other wine. A good wine should have character.
Chewy; The sense of thickness and abundance of tannins that is not overwhelming.
Chocolaty; A term that describes flavors often used of rich red wines such as Cabernet Sauvignon and Pinot noir.
Citrous; A wine with the aromas and flavor from citrus.
Clean; A wine that is not demonstrating any obvious faults or unwanted aromas and flavors.
Clear; A wine with no visible particular matter.
Closed; A wine that is not very aromatic.
Compact; Opposite of "open knit". A wine with a dense perception fruit that is balanced by the weight of tannins and acidity.
Complex; A wine that has many different flavors and aromas.
Corked; A tasting term for a wine that has cork taint.
Creamy; A term used to describe the perception of a warm, creamy mouthfeel. 
Crisp; A pleasing sense of acidity in the wine. Usually associated with the acidity in white wine, this denotes a fresh, light character.
Decan;t/Decanting Pouring wine from its original bottle into another container (decanter), allowing the wine to “breathe”. 
Delicate; Light texture and subtle flavors. A delicate wine should not be paired with highly flavored foods.
Depth; A term used to denote a wine with several layers of flavor. An aspect of complexity.
Dry; A wine that is lacking the perception of sweetness.
Dried; up A wine that has lost some of its freshness or fruitiness due to extended aging.
Earthy; More often used to describe European wines, these have aromas and flavors resembling the earth, perhaps even soil or rock.
Edgy; A wine with a noticeably level of acidity that heightens the flavors on the palate. 
Elegant; A term to describe a wine that possess finesse with subtle flavors that are in balance.
Farmyard; A term used to describe the earthy and vegetal undertones that some Chardonnay and Pinot noir develop after maturing in the bottle. It may be a sign that the wine has entered its peak drinking period.
Fermentation; The process of adding yeast to crushed grapes to turn their sugar into alcohol. 
Finish; The sense and perception of the wine after swallowing.
Finesse; A very subjective term used to describe a wine of high quality that is well balanced.
Firm; A stronger sense of tannins.
Flat; In relation to sparkling wines, flat refers to a wine that has lost its effervescence. In all other wines the term is used to denote a wine that is lacking acidity, particularly on the finish. 
Fresh; A positive perception of acidity.
Fruit; One of the wine descriptions used when a wine imparts prominent fruit flavors and aromas. 
Ful;l-Bodied A wine which fills the mouth with flavors and alcohol. A full-bodied wine is also considered “thick”. It can also refer to a wine that is full in flavor and extract.
Grapey; A wine with the aromas and flavors reminiscent of grape flavoring. Muscat grapes often produce wines that are described as "grapey".
Grassy; A term used to describe an herbaceous or vegetal element of a wine--ranging from freshly mown lawn grass to lemon grass flavors.
Green; Overly acidic wine. Typically used to describe a wine made from unripe fruit.
Hard; Overly tannic wine.
Harsh; Too much acid or tannin describes these rough, biting wines. They generally lack fruit.
Heavy; A wine that is very alcoholic with too much sense of body.
Hollow; A wine lacking the sense of fruit.
Hot; Overly alcoholic wine.
Lean; The sense of acidity in the wine that lacks a perception of fruit.
Legs; The tracks of liquid that cling to the sides of a glass after the contents have been swirled. Often said to be related to the alcohol or glycerol content of a wine. Also called tears.
Liquorice; A term used to describe the concentrated flavor from rich sweet wines which are produced by botrytized grapes.
Magnum; A wine bottle holding twice the wine (1500 ml) than the average bottle (750 ml).
Mature; A wine that has aged to its peak point of quality.
Mellow; A wine with a soft texture that is nearing the peak of its maturity.
Meritage; A term used by California wine producers to describe their wines blended from Bordeaux varieties. It was designed to indicate a wine blend of higher quality than a “table wine” and without infringing on the name Bordeaux. 
Minerality; A sense of mineral in the wine.
Nose; A tasting term for the aroma or bouquet of a wine.
Oaky; A wine with a noticeable perception of the effects of oak. This can include the sense of vanilla, sweet spice, a creamy body and a smoky or toasted flavor.
Oily; A generally full bodied wine with a viscous mouthfeel. 
Opulent; A rich tasting wine with a pleasing texture mouthfeel that is well balanced.
Oxidized; A generally negative term describing a wine that has experienced too much exposure to oxidation. A wine that has been oxidized, is considered faulty and may exhibit sherry-like odors.
Palate; How one perceives the taste and flavor of wine in the mouth.
Peak; The point where a wine is at its most ideal drinking conditions for an individual taster. This is a very subjective determination as for some tasters a wine will be at its peak when the fruit is still fresh and young while for some tasters the peak will arrive when a wine has matured in flavor.
Peppery; A wine with the aromas and flavors reminiscent of peppercorn.
Perfume; A generally positively used to describe an aspect of a wine's aroma or bouquet.
Plum; A wine with the juicy, fresh fruit flavors of plum.
Powerful; A wine with a high level of alcohol that is not excessively alcoholic.
Rich; A sense of sweetness in the wine that is not excessively sweet.
Robust; A term with similar connotations as "aggressive" except that "robust" is more commonly applied to older, mature wines while "aggressive" tends to describe younger wines.
Round; A wine that has a good sense of body that is not overly tannic.
Sediment; The non-liquid material at the bottom of a bottle of wine. Sediment is not detrimental and simply part of the wine.
Sharp; A term normally used to describe the acidity of a wine though it can refer to the degree of bitterness derived from a wine's tannin.
Short; A wine with well develop aromas and mouthfeel but has a finish that is little to non-existent due to the fruit quickly disappearing after swallowing.
Smokey; A wine exhibiting the aromas and flavors of the various types of smoke derived from oak influences.
Smooth; A wine with a pleasing texture. Typically refers to a wine with soft tannins.
Soft; A wine that is not overly tannic.
Sommelier; The restaurant specialist who has considerable wine knowledge and assists guests with their wine selection.
Spicy; A wine with aromas and flavors reminiscent of various spices such mint, clove, cinnamon, vanilla or pepper
Sweet; A wine with a noticeable sense of sugar levels. "Sweet" is one of the wine definitions easily confused with "fruity". Sweet indicates the presence of residual sugar, left over when the grape juice is converted to alcohol. Some dry wines have an aroma of sweetness that in reality comes from ripe fruit flavors.
Tannin; An ingredient found naturally in the skins, seeds and stems of grapes. Tannins are usually found in red wines and give that dry, lip puckering sensation. Tannins are an important component in red wine and soften with age.
Tannic; A wine with aggressive tannins.
Tart; A wine with high levels of acidity.
Thin; A wine that is lacking body or fruit
Tight; A wine with a significant presence of tannins that is restraining the other qualities of the wine, such as fruit and extract, from being more noticeable. A "tight wine" is expected to age well as the tannins soften to reveal these other qualities.
Unoaked; Also known as unwooded, refers to wines that have been matured without contact with wood/oak such as in aging barrels.
Undertone; The more subtle nuances, aromas and flavors of wine.
Vanilla; An oak induced characteristic aroma reminiscent of vanilla.
Varietal; Wine that is made from one dominant grape variety and whose labels states so.
Vintage; The year the wine is harvested.
Vivid; A wine with very expressive ripe, fruit flavors.
Voluptuous; A wine with a full body and rich texture.
Warm; A wine with noticeable but balanced alcohol as opposed to a wine with excessive alcohol that maybe described as "hot". It can also refer to a creamy texture derived from oak treatment.
Watery; A wine that is excessively "thin" in body and fruit.
Yeasty; Often uses synonymously with "biscuity" and can describe a wine with aromas and flavor reminiscent of bread dough or biscuits.
Young; Wine that is not matured and usually bottled and sold within a year of its vintage.
Zesty; A wine with noticeable acidity and usually citrus notes.
